<br>
These fission jackets are optional.<br>
<br>
The fissionable pusher/tamper is an integral (and optional)  part of the second, third, or so on, stage NOT a separate stage unto itself.<br>
<br>
Tsar Bomba yielded somewhere between 50 and 60 megatons.<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://nuketesting.enviroweb.org/hew/Russia/Tsarbmb.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
The weapon was capable of reaching 100 mt if a fissionable jacket was used on the third stage. This would have added the fallout equivalent of 25% of all the atmospheric testing combined. Fortunately, the Soviets chose not to test it that way.<br>
<br>
The largest US test was Bravo, at 15 mt. It was a runaway and most afrighted the participents.<br>
<br>
The 25 mt Mk-41 was never tested at that yield.<br>
<br>
Both Tsar Bomba and Mk-41 were three stage devices.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
The mk-41 stages were {fission}{fusion}{fusion-fission}<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
Most Thermonuclear weapons were two stage like this:<br>
<br>
{fission}{fusion-fission}<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
The neutron bomb would stage this way:<br>
<br>
{fission}{fusion}<br>
